[normal]Bahram[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Bekhradnia[bold], Director, Hi
[normal]gher Education Policy Institute
[normal], 
[normal]Dr[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Andrew[bold]&#xa0;[bold]McGettigan[bold], Author and Expert on University Funding, HEPI, and 
[normal]Toni[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Pearce[bold], President, National Union of Students, gave evidence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Good morning and welcome.  I should explain that in the temporary absence of one of our witnesses, we took the opportunity to complete another piece of business, but now we have the complete team here, so we can start.  Can I welcome you and thank you for agreeing to give evidence at this inquiry?  Just before we start the questioning, if you could introduce yourselves for voice transcription purposes that would be very helpful.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: Hi, I am Toni; I am the President of the National 
[normal]Union
[normal] of Students.
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: I am Bahram
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Bekhradnia; I am Director of the Higher Education Policy Institute.
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: I am Andrew
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]McGettigan.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] To start with a fairly general question—well, my first one is not that general.  It is, in fact, to you, Toni.  Taking your written evidence, you said that, in principle—I quote—you do not believe that “the loan book, a public asset, should be sold into private hands”.  Could you just explain what the reasoning is for that assertion?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: Absolutely.  I think that the really important thing here is the way that people feel about where they borrow money from and who they owe money to.  Particularly the 
[normal]compact that individuals, and students particularly, feel that they have with the state when it comes to higher education funding is really important.  Although in many ways the funding system itself undermines that, a compact between the student and the state is really important in terms of who pays for their education.  A lot of my members’ concerns are 
[normal]about
[normal] who they owe their money to and who they are paying, and whether that is going to benefit private interests or whether it is going to fund education.  That is a really difficult and tough concern for them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Could you not accept that it is in the best interests of students and the system overall to have an efficient process to collect debt, and that the NAO found that the Government could find a more efficient collection of debt by employing a private company?
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: On your first point, I do think that it is definitely in the interests of students, and of taxpayers more generally, that there is an efficient way of collecting student debt.  I do not necessarily believe that an efficient way of collecting student debt is to sell off an asset for less than it is worth to benefit a short
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term political interest.  
[normal]I
[normal]f we look more carefully at efficiency specifically, I would suggest that the most efficient way of collecting debt or tax or payment from an individual is through a PAYE or a tax system, and if that system is not efficient, I would have real questions more fundamentally about how we collect money from individuals who owe money to the state.  
[normal]The other thing I would be really concerned about is the tactics that private interests might employ, working on behalf of the Government or the state, to recoup that money.  I would be really worried about individuals facing bailiffs or more aggressive debt collection tactics by a private interest working on behalf of the state.  I have not felt reassured that that has been considered
[normal],
[normal] explained
[normal],
[normal] communicated or talked about.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] In a previous incarnation, I was chair of a very large local authority finance department, and we used private bodies to collect debt.  Provid
[normal]ed
[normal] you get the balance right—and there is no God
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]given reason why they should not be able to—a public organisation employing the private sector, with the appropriate regulation, may well be able to deliver more effectively.  Would you not accept that?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: That is probably hypothetically possible.  I do not know if that has been explored, communicated or tested in this example.  I do not know that there is any evidence to suggest that this system would be more efficient, and I genuinely believe that students more broadly and more deeply have a greater concern about where their money sits, where their money is being invested and who they are investing it with.
[normal]Chair:[bold] Yes, I am sure that there are some students there, but if they are not, shall we say, paying the money, in some cases, then I think they have rather lost that right to be concerned.  However, we have probably explored this issue as fully as we can.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] I just want to understand a little more.  I am not quite sure whether your objection is
[normal] to
[normal] the hard
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]faced men in the City, or whether your concern is that heavies might be sent round to knock on the door in order to reclaim the money.  I am not quite sure where your argument is really coming from.
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: Firstly, I suppose any objections I have to hard
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]faced men in the City are probably outside of this concern.  I think that the funding of higher education and education generally should be done through a compact between the state and the individual, and that is a system that this was designed to deliver.  When you sell off a huge chunk of that system for much less than it is worth to a private investment company, you change that relationship and you change the terms of that relationship, because your relationship is not with the state any
[normal] 
[normal]more; it is with investors.  There is a real feeling of concern, and all I can do here is try to convey the feeling of concern that I get from my members.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] I have only heard you mention the taxpayer once.  They have a concern too, and they have a real concern that this money is not being collected, and that many people are not paying back what they are borrowing. It is a straightforward situation of people borrowing and needing to pay it back, and our only issue is how we ensure that happens as effectively as possible in the interests of the taxpayer.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: I am a taxpayer and I am interested in making sure that that money is recouped, partly because I am interested in the finances of the country and I am interested in our economic situation.  However, I do not believe that it is in my interests or the interests of the taxpayer to sell off a chunk of student loans for much less than they are worth and to bring in a small amount of that money to fix a short-term financial or political problem; I do not think
[normal] that
[normal] is in my interests.  With the lack of consultation with taxpayers or students before this is done, and the lack of understanding about this happening, you would be hard-pressed to find out what the feeling is from the taxpayer generally.
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] Or the student body, actually, but never mind.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Could I just mention as an aside that certainly I and Members of this Committee have been very concerned in another context about the under
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]valuing of national assets being sold off, but I have not found any evidence that this is the case here
[normal].
[normal]  In fact, if anything, the evidence appears to go the other way.  However, could I just make the point to you that the Student Loans Company has employed, if you like, debt management or debt collection companies to get loans from abroad, because obviously HMRC has no writ there
[normal].
[normal]  Do you object to that?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: What I object to is a lack of understanding about how this private company or any private company would use those tactics.  This is about transparency and an understanding of how this works, and I think that not necessarily students but people who take out these loans that have been sold do not understand that and have not been communicated to about how that will work.  I do have concerns about the welfare of people who, for whatever reason, whether that is disability or mental health problems or long
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term unemployment, are not able to meet these payments and do not understand the system that requires you to defer annually your loan repayment when we have changed since then the loan system of higher education several times.  For a lot of people
[normal],
[normal] maybe that is difficult to understand.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q8 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I just fail to see how somebody who has taken out a loan can object to legitimate ways of collecting the unpaid loans from other persons who have taken out loans, and that there 
[normal]is a, shall we say, overriding responsibility to provide value to the taxpayer of whichever body happens to own that loan book.  Would you not accept that there is that?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: There is an overriding responsibility to collect that money back.  There is an overriding responsibility to give taxpayers value for money in terms of these assets, and I do not think, personally, that that is what has happened.  Yes, the employment of legitimate debt
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]collection tactics is of course acceptable, but I have asked the question several times about how this would be done and whether we have an idea of how these private companies work and what their ethic is and what their values are.  In fact, they are acting on behalf of Government when they collect these debts, whether that loan has been sold or not.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q9 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] It does seem to me that you are being rather presumptuous, but can I now talk to Dr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]McGettigan.  This is really about the calculation of the loans and the loan book.  You have suggested, in calculating returns from the sale of the loan book,
[normal] 
[normal]that 
[normal]the Government ha
[normal]ve
[normal] neglected to include the loss of £1.7
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion in lost revenue from repayments.  Can you just explain that? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: Could I clarify
[normal]?
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]e are talking about two different loan book sales here?  I think your questions to Toni were about the sale of the remaining tranche of the mortgage
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]style loans, where the question of value for money is quite different, because we are talking about very different kinds of loans that were not collected through HMRC.  The sale of loans 
[normal]that 
[normal]we are talking about now 
[normal]is of
[normal] the ones announced formally in the 
[normal]s
[normal]pending 
[normal]r
[normal]ound and recently reaffirmed in the Autumn Statement.  The main issue there is that the declared proceeds of this sale projected over the five years, starting in 2015-16, as outlined in table 2.5 of the Autumn
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Statement, are gross proceeds.  They are not net proceeds, so what is not included in those tables is the income stream you have sold to the private provider.  There is another £1.7
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion from 2016-17 and 2017-18 and 2018-19 that you have to net out of that gross calculation, because that is precisely what you have sold to the purchasers.  There will then be subsequent repayments in future years that are also now going to the purchasers and not to the Government.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q10 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Can I just get it clear in my own mind?  You are saying that the Government ha
[normal]ve
[normal] based 
[normal]their 
[normal]financial projections on the figures that presumably 
[normal]they
[normal] would get theoretically if there was no loss of repayment by virtue of people not reaching the income threshold or defaulting or what?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: No, there are projections based on the OBR and figures that BIS had provided to the OBR showing what a graduate repayment is likely to be in future years, so we send the loans out into the world and we model repayments coming back.  We have figures that you can see in the 
[normal]Economic and fiscal outlook
[normal] from the OBR that were published in June.  They show what the projections for repayments are expected to be up to 2017-18.  They have to be revised down because you have sold part of that income stream, and that is what I am saying is missing from table
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5 of the Autumn
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Statement.  It shows gross proceeds, not net proceeds, because you have said how much money we are getting in from the private sector for purchasing the loans, but you are not showing how much income you previously thought you were getting in that is now going to other hands.
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: Just to clarify that, I do not think Andrew is saying that the Government ha
[normal]ve
[normal] not taken that into account in their calculations.  The Government 
[normal]have 
[normal]not shown that in what they have shown us of the consequences of the sale.  That, I think, is what is being said there.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q11 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Paul Blomfield:[bold] 
[normal]That suggests that is significant misrepresentation of the benefits.  Can you just quantify that?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: According to the calculations that you can do on the basis of what is in the OBR’s 
[normal]Economic and fiscal outlook
[normal] published in December, £200
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million is missing from 2016-17, £500
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million from 2017-18 and £1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion from 2018-19.  The years after, 2019-20 and 2020-21, there is another billion.  Effectively, you are getting the proceeds up front for the sale, but what the private sector is buying is a future income stream, and that is what is not being factored into the impact assessment here.  I am saying
[normal] that
[normal] that is for the five
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year period; there are long-term implications of this that are not being considered at all.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q12 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] You are saying that it is not just that they have miscalculated the amount; they have not included it at all.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: It is omitted.  I will go so far.  I do not know whether it is a presentational decision to omit it or if they have misunderstood the nature of financial assets.  That is a question you will have to put to the Treasury.  The thing is it looks like they are pretending they have sold a physical asset and you just have the money in but you no longer have the physical asset.  However, the valuation of financial assets is you are selling something that gives you a future income stream, and in this case we are talking about loans with 30-year or 35
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year lifetimes.  Therefore, if you sell an income stream on that basis there is a long-term implication here, and I am saying they have got the short
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term presentation wrong; who knows what they got wrong about the long
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term presentation?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q13 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] They have not included the income stream, whether it is discounted for other factors or not.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan: [bold]Yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q14 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Bain:[bold] From what you have just said, it would appear that over the five
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year period of the OBR forecast, there is no net benefit to the taxpayer at all.  Would that be a fair representation of what you have just said?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: There is a net benefit in the short term, because you are getting cash up front.  What I am saying is that that is mis
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]presented and, in fact, there is an extremely important point, which is you are only showing the time
[normal] 
[normal]frame up to 2018-19.  On that point, yes, you get more cash in and you can say that you are reducing net debt as a result of the sale as well as covering the additional loan outlay.  The problem is once you start looking at 2019-20 and 2020-21, those figures suddenly change dramatically because your sale proceeds have run out, you are issuing £2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion of extra loans and you have £1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion less of income than you had previously.  You have to find a net £3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion to cover the expansion.  You have lost 
[normal]the repayments, you are issuing more loans, the sale proceeds have run out and then you have to start thinking about what happens subsequently.  If you only show the first four years or the first five years, you can just about make some claims, but they are not as good as they look and the long
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term implications are what you should really be focusing on.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q15 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] Can I just ask a supplementary, as a very simple businessman?  Are you saying that the people who bought the loans in the first place are getting a better deal than the Government ha
[normal]ve
[normal] suggested they are getting?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: There are two different loans, but I will answer that question because it is important.
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] It is an important question.
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: There are two loan sales at issue.  There are the loans that were sold in 1998 and 1999.
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] I understand that.
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: The Government ha
[normal]ve
[normal] subsidised that purchase and, according to the accounts published in 2012-13, that subsidy is currently valued at £250
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million.  In order to get in £2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion of cash up front, effectively £3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion in today’s prices, the Government 
[normal]were
[normal] prepared to lose £250
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million over the long run.  It is more than expected, but yes, that is the nature of these sales.  You have to compensate the purchasers for the lack of control over the terms and conditions, and if RPI and interest rates move in the way they have, there are contracts that say, in the event of certain circumstances, future payments have to go from the Government to the purchasers to compensate for the fact that they cannot control these terms and conditions. With the mortgage
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]style loans, the issue is largely the very high repayment threshold
[normal]. 
[normal]The repayment threshold on the mortgage loans that have just been sold is £28,775, so no one starts repaying them until they earn over that.
[normal] 
[normal]Obviously, that makes a huge difference to the value of that loan in terms of how much income you are going to get from it.  
[normal]Here, what I have just been talking about in answer to Paul’s question and 
[normal]Adrian
[normal]’s question is the sale of the much, much bigger income
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]contingent repayment loans, where there is a projection that the Government will try to raise £10
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion to £12
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion over the next five years.  That may involve selling up to £20
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion worth of loans in face
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]value terms, so you could be shifting almost the entire stock of loans issued prior to 
[normal]2010, in
[normal] order to raise that kind of sum.  Again, you will need to compensate purchasers for the current interest rate terms.  Those graduates who borrowed money to go through university have interest rate terms that say interest accrues at the lower of RPI or bank base rates plus one.  Bank base rates have been 0.5%
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]since 2009.  That means there is an effective interest rate on those loans of 1.5% whereas RPI is currently 3.3%.  No purchaser is going to buy an investment that is earning lower than RPI inflation.  Therefore, you have to devise a contract to get round that
[normal],
[normal] and that will involve payments.  
[normal]We are not talking about lost repayments now; we are talking cash payments the Government will make to purchasers in 2030 or 2040, so well beyond the horizons of things like the 
[normal]Economic and fiscal outlook
[normal] and the Autumn
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Statement.  That is where the value
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]for
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]money question becomes crucial, because you have to say, “How much do I get up front, how much 
[normal]repayment income am I selling and what subsidies am I committing a future Government to pay?”  It is extremely difficult for anybody to make an accurate projection of that
[normal],
[normal] for obvious reasons.  Value for money is not going to come down to a test where you can say, “Okay, that is value for money and that is not”.  It is going to be a whole series of judgments and that is the place for a Committee like this to interrogate how that is being put together.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q16 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Can I just make it clear, first of all, 
[normal]that 
[normal]the loan book that is being sold is the old loan book?  I think everybody needs to be clear on that.  What we are talking about in the Autumn
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Statement is the projected sale of the current loan book.  I do understand that BIS has said a final decision to go ahead with the sale has not yet been taken.  Any decision will require a full assessment of the value for money to the taxpayer of selling the loans against the cost to Government of retaining them.  What is your assessment of that?  Do you think it is worth selling them?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: There is no way that the Government will get more money than it is worth.  The problem is what the upfront price will be, what the assessment of the fair value of the income stream associated with the loan asset is and what the terms of the contract are.  What are you committing future Governments to pay to compensate purchasers when certain macro
[normal]-
[normal]economic conditions move against the purchasers?  In that case, it will undoubtedly lose money in the same way that the other sale has lost money.  It is just about what the short
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term benefits are.  Everything we are being presented with from the Treasury is the short term benefit: how does this change the net cash position in the short term?  How does this change the public sector net debt in the short term?  What does this mean for the short
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term expansion—unsustainable expansion—of higher education numbers?  Everything about the sale has been presented in the short term.  The question of value for money is the long term.  
[normal]You are not going to sell an asset for more than it is effectively worth to the Government, so the detail is going to be about what else is being committed.  The upfront price might look quite good.  The upfront price in 1998 or 1999 looked like the face value of the loans; it was £1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion up front for what was valued at slightly over £1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion.  It is about what other payments go the other way to compensate the purchaser; that is where the real question of value for money lies.  Nobody in 1998 or 1999 would predict what interest rates would be in 2009 and subsequently.  That moved against them, so the deal ended up worse than even they thought they were going to lose on it.  That is where the real test is and, again, it is a question of long-term responsibility.  We have a long-term financial asset here, but short-term politics is driving things that make the headline statistics look better.  Obviously, we have a Government 
[normal]who
[normal] presented macro
[normal]-
[normal]economic competence to the public through the deficit and the debt.  That is short-term accounting driving long-term economic decisions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q17 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Nadhim Zahawi:[bold] Andrew, you mentioned the one historic example where you said the Government brought in about £2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion—£3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion in today’s money—but the additional cost was £250
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million, is that right?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: The initial projected net present value of the subsidy on those two sales was thought to be about £125
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million to £130
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million, so at the time the decision was made it was estimated that there would be a long-run loss on the sale.  
[normal]&#xa0;
