[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q23 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Nadhim Zahawi:[bold] And you think that is not such a good thing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: Why would the Government be using this kind of business method?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q24 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Nadhim Zahawi:[bold] Forget the Government.  Do you think it is a good idea that you bring in £2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion or £3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion now—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan[bold]: Now we are talking about £10
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion or £12
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion and in five years’ time we will be talking about the new loans issued, which are worth £15
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion every year.  What is the scale of loss then, on that?  That is the question I would put to you.  When we start talking about hundreds of millions, or maybe a billion, lost in the long run, at what point do we say, “Why 
[normal]are
[normal] the Government doing this?”  There is no liquidity constraint.  You can issue bonds if you need this money.  I think it is bad for Government; it makes sense for a business with expansion plans.
[normal]&#xa0;
