[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q77 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] That is very helpful, thank you.  I am not sure the other questions are worth asking either.  You have rerun the model to allow for your assumptions; please would you outline what lessons you have learn
[normal]ed
[normal]?  Do you want to write to us? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: What lessons we have learned?  The main one is the one that I mentioned: that the model is okay—I have got no problem with the model—but it is the assumptions that go into it, and the parameters.  The main one is the dispersion of income growth, which there is no basis for.  To take the mean and apply that to the model, when that 
[normal]i
[normal]s known not to apply seems
[normal] to be a bizarre thing to do.  It would be much better if they were to make a more realistic assumption about the dispersion of income growth. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q78 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] You just question their judgment again? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]:  On that, most certainly, yes.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q79 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] This all comes down to a punt, does it not really, at the end of the day? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]:  To be honest, no, that does not.  We have evidence for how income growth has varied over the last 50 years—
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] I understand that. 
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: I think they should make use of the evidence that exists. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q80 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] Sure, but the basic judgments come down to a punt, and that was one of the words you used way back in the 
[normal]session
[normal]. Let me ask the final one, just 
[normal]for
[normal] the fun of it, as they say, because it is here.  Have you told the Government about any improvements that you have made to 
[normal]their 
[normal]model and, if you have, how has the Department responded?  This is a real curtain-closer.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: Of course we have.  
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] I thought you would have. 
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: We publish everything that we produce and even what we think.  The response of the Government was to describe our analysis as “eccentric”, as the Minister did in the House of Commons.  The Minister for Universities wrote in 
[normal]The Independent
[normal] that we had taken the most pessimistic assumption possible on every parameter; actually, a year later, he has moved very close to where we were.  The Secretary of State came here, I think to your Committee a year ago, and expressed astonishment that anybody could think that the student fee increase would impact on inflation and therefore eventually on pensions, and a week later the Office for National Statistics published the inflation rate and said that 0.2 percentage points of that inflation rate were—
[normal]Chair:[bold] He also described the Royal Mail share price as “froth”. 
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: Whatever, but in relation to our business, we do an honest job and we say what we think is right, and unfortunately Minsters are protected by armour, and so it takes a Committee like this to try to get behind that armour. 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] We sometimes do. 
[normal]Dr McGettigan:[bold] I would just say again I think it is the accounting that I would be more concerned about: how you account for the RAB charge change two or three years ago; the accounts for how you treat the amortisation of loans 
[normal]were
[normal] changed last financial year.  It is very hard to follow these fluctuations through the accounts and what is going on, and the 
[normal]various notes that I have put in the written submission—particularly note 32 and note 20—there are no workings there; you get these figures, but there is no real way to assess what that movement of £30 million meant, and what that movement of £70 million meant.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q81 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] You are crystal-ball gazing, are you not, all the time?  
[normal]&#xa0;
