[normal]was
[normal] able to do with the estimated repayments, but what is happening in their books we do not see the workings; we do not see the assumptions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q82 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Bain:[bold] Earlier this year
[normal],
[normal] the Department asked the Student Loans Company to carry out a strategic review of its collection process; that is the first such review that occurred in four years.  The Student Loans Company identified the following three strategic objectives: the first is to implement measures to maximise collection of repayments due, and information about those who are or who are not repaying in order to allow accurate forecasting; the second was to improve customer service while making it easier for borrowers to understand their repayment arrangements and to fulfil their repayment obligations; and the third was to improve the efficiency of the Student Loans Company’s collections operation.  
[normal]              
[normal]Now, it is interesting that the Student Loans Company has not yet specified the overall performance improvements that it is seeking to obtain from having gone through this strategy.  Can I put to all members of the panel
[normal] this question?
[normal] What measures do you think would be beneficial to maximise collection rates? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: I think the first and third of those objectives are to some degree in conflict.  Maximising income can be done, 
[normal]as 
[normal]we said earlier, but in some cases at huge cost.  If you are going to appoint lawyers in 
[normal]Bulgaria
[normal] to chase through the Bulgarian courts the non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]payers from 
[normal]Bulgaria
[normal], and repeat that for every one of the other 25 countries, you are engaging in a huge operation at huge cost.  I am not sure it would be effi
[normal]cient.  
[normal]I am not sure that measures to maximise your income is necessarily a wise thing to do, but, on the other hand, I think you probably have to appear to be attempting to maximise your income in order to encourage people to repay.  
[normal]Dr McGettigan:[bold] I would agree with what the NAO suggests, which is 
[normal]that 
[normal]you need a clear understanding of what is receivable and what is received, so that you know what repayments you ought to be getting, and things on defaulting
[normal] and so on
[normal] are clearer.  There is an inevitable lag with income-contingent repayment loans, because you have to determine what people’s earnings were in a year before you can determine what is due from them.  With graduate employment churn at the moment
[normal],
[normal] that is not a str
[normal]aightforward matter, so there are
[normal] inevitably going to be some lags in this, and determining those issues is going to be much more complex than it is for the fixed-period repayment loans—the old mortgage-style loans
[normal]—
[normal]where the debt is paid off in 60 tranches, and you set up a direct debit once you have gone over the repayment t
[normal]hreshold. Here, with
[normal] the mandatory repayments being determined by what people were earning, not just the debit borrowed, everything becomes more complicated. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q83 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Bain:[bold] It is a very interesting point this one, because if we look at what has happened over the last three to four decades, particularly for employees in the lower half of the income scale, the share of the economy that has gone in wages to them has declined over that period.  
[normal]There is no evidence that it is going to suddenly pick up in the next 10, 20 or 30 years either, without big changes in Government policy.  What impact do you think that has on the Student Loans Company when it is evaluating how much income it is likely to be able to get back?  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan:[bold] Technically
[normal],
[normal] those estimates are being done elsewhere; they are being done at BIS or the OBR, or some mix of the two.  Again, it comes back to how this then translate
[normal]s
[normal] into budgets and accounting.  What are the pressures?  How much information lag—clearly everyone is in agreement that if there 
[normal]are
[normal] concerted efforts to avoid payment
[normal], 
[normal]that is a different matter from predicting what the macro-economy is going to look like so you can accurately assess what repayments are going to look like.  The NAO is right 
[normal]in 
[normal]saying, “We do not know here what in the short term is due to what”.  Is it poor collection performance, or is it poor ability to predict the macro
[normal]economic conditions?
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: I would agree with what both Bahram and Andrew said, but there is another role that strategically the Student Loans Company inevitably will have to see 
[normal]itself
[normal] playing, in the absence of an HE bill, and with 
[normal]it 
[normal]being the 
[normal]body that has 
[normal]the power to designate courses at private providers.  When we see a black hole in finances created by over
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]recruitment at for-profit providers that have been designated by the SLC to have access to the public loan book, the SLC needs to see one of its priorities as stepping up to strategically address that issue of where we designate access to the student loan book, particularly 
[normal]for
[normal] private providers.  If 
[normal]it was 
[normal]given more power, or if 
[normal]it was 
[normal]able to use that power more effectively, perhaps we would not have found ourselves in the situation we have done with private HNC and HND over
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]recruitment. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q84 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Bain:[bold] Are all or any of you confident that the people who are taking out these loans understand fully what they are getting into?  Do they understand the obligations that they are going to have to meet in terms of repaying these loans?  Is that something that you are picking up? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Toni Pearce[bold]: It is similar to the question earlier.  I would hope that the majority of students who take out loans understand what they are getting themselves into.  The real key is what they are getting themselves into at that point in time.  What they do not know, and what they cannot know and nobody can predict, is what might happen to the terms and conditions of their loan in the future.  I suppose that 
[normal]it 
[normal]is really concerning, particularly for somebody who is debt averse, or who does not understand the technicalities of debt or finance, to
[normal] be told,
[normal] “This is a set of terms and conditions, so you should learn what they mean, but they could change at any time, and it probably will not be a very public change.
[normal]”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dr McGettigan:[bold] It is worth stressing that the details of the loans are administrative matters for the Secretary of State to determine, so you have got the repayment threshold, the rate above the threshold, the interest rate, and the write
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]off period, which are all matters that do not need primary legislation to change; it is a secondary matter.  Page 8 of 
[normal]Student Loans - A Guide to Terms and Conditions
[normal] says, “You must agree to repay your loan in line with the regulations that apply at the time the repayments are due, and as they’re amended.  The regulations may be replaced by later regulations.”  
[normal]These students do not have fixed terms and conditions; they are exempt from the Consumer Credit Act of 1974.  That is a big change from the old mortgage-style loans, where the terms 
[normal]were fixed and they were included in that agreement.  If you are going to try to collect more from people, and make more of an issue of whether they have understood the terms and conditions, you have got to fix the terms and conditions when people take out the loans.  You cannot have this situation where terms and conditions can be amended later.  There has to be give and take here from Parliament and from the Government on this.  
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: I would agree with both those points.  I think that one of the things the Government ha
[normal]ve
[normal] done well is to sell but also explain the financing system, but nevertheless it remains the case that the terms of the loans are changeable.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q85 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Bain:[bold] Final point: the NAO recommended in 
[normal]its
[normal] report that the Student Loans Company should use debt collection agencies to improve the efficiency of the collection operation.  What are your reflections on that recommendation? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: As has been said already, I think that if a loan is due and has not been paid then the Student Loans Company needs to take steps to collect it.  I would not bring in a debt collection company as the first thing to do, but it is a tool in their armoury.  I would not pick it out—
[normal]Chair:[bold] Okay, fairly short answers on this, because I want to bring in Andrew.  
[normal]              [bold]Bahram Bekhradnia[bold]: That is my answer. 
[normal]&#xa0;
